THE East African Community (EAC) member states have been urged to seek the root causes of the refugee problem in the region, find a solution and integrate refugee management in national development plans. The sentiments were voiced in the East African Legislative Assembly (EALA) and was part of a wide debate in its chamber here last week. The regional assembly is emphatic that partner states are duty bound to undertake a deliberate and conscious effort to address the root causes of conflicts in the region. It has also been stressed that mainstreaming the needs of refugee women, children and youth in national and regional development plans should be prioritised as well as the advocacy for equitable resource distribution as envisaged under the United Nations (UN)â€™ Global Compact Initiatives for refuge management. The assembly has adopted a report of the Committee on Regional Affairs and Conflict Resolution on the Oversight activity to the refugee hosting